# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: background-jobs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] In computing, **batch processing** is the running of a software job in an automated and unattended way.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] A user schedules a job to run and then waits for a processing system to run it.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Typically, a job is scheduled to run at a configured time of day or when an event occurs or when computer resources are available.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] The term "batch processing" originates in the traditional classification of methods of production as job production (one-off production), batch production (production of a "batch" of multiple items at once, one stage at a time), and flow production (mass production, all stages in process at once).
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Early computers were capable of running only one program at a time.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Each user had sole control of the machine for a scheduled period of time.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] They would arrive at the computer with program and data, often on punched paper cards and magnetic or paper tape, and would load their program, run and debug it, and carry off their output when done.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] As computers became faster the setup and takedown time became a larger percentage of available computer time.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Programs called *monitors*, the forerunners of operating systems, were developed which could process a series, or "batch", of programs, often from magnetic tape prepared offline.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] The monitor would be loaded into the computer and run the first job of the batch.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] At the end of the job it would regain control and load and run the next until the batch was complete.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Often the output of the batch would be written to magnetic tape and printed or punched offline.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Examples of monitors were IBM's *Fortran Monitor System*, SOS (Share Operating System), and finally IBSYS for IBM's 709x systems in 1960.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Third-generation computers capable of multiprogramming began to appear in the 1960s.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Instead of running one batch job at a time, these systems can have multiple batch programs running at the same time in order to keep the system as busy as possible.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] One or more programs might be awaiting input, one actively running on the CPU, and others generating output.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Instead of offline input and output, programs called spoolers read jobs from cards, disk, or remote terminals and place them in a job queue to be run.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] In order to prevent deadlocks the job scheduler needs to know each job's resource requirements—memory, magnetic tapes, mountable disks, etc., so various scripting languages were developed to supply this information in a structured way.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Probably the most well-known is IBM's *Job Control Language* (JCL).
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Job schedulers select jobs to run according to a variety of criteria, including priority, memory size, etc.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Remote batch is a procedure for submitting batch jobs from remote terminals, often equipped with a punch card reader and a line printer.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Sometimes asymmetric multiprocessing is used to spool batch input and output for one or more large computers using an attached smaller and less-expensive system, as in the IBM System/360 Attached Support Processor.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] The first general-purpose time-sharing system, Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), was compatible with batch processing.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] This facilitated transitioning from batch processing to interactive computing.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] From the late 1960s onwards, interactive computing such as via text-based computer terminal interfaces (as in Unix shells or read-eval-print loops), and later graphical user interfaces became common.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation, both one-off jobs such as compilation, and processing of multiple items in batches, became retrospectively referred to as *batch processing*, and the term *batch job* (in early use often "batch *of* jobs") became common.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Early use is particularly found at the University of Michigan, around the Michigan Terminal System (MTS).
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Although timesharing did exist, its use was not robust enough for corporate data processing; none of this was related to the earlier unit record equipment, which was human-operated.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation remains widespread in computing, both for general data processing and for system "housekeeping" tasks (using system software).
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] A high-level program (executing multiple programs, with some additional "glue" logic) is today most often called a *script*, and written in scripting languages, particularly shell scripts for system tasks; in IBM PC DOS and MS-DOS this is instead known as a batch file.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] That includes UNIX-based computers, Microsoft Windows, macOS (whose foundation is the BSD Unix kernel), and even smartphones.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] A running script, particularly one executed from an interactive login session, is often known as a job, but that term is used very ambiguously.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] "There is no direct counterpart to z/OS batch processing in PC or UNIX systems.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Batch jobs are typically executed at a scheduled time or on an as-needed basis.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Batch applications are still critical in most organizations in large part because many common business processes are amenable to batch processing.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] While online systems can also function when manual intervention is not desired, they are not typically optimized to perform high-volume, repetitive tasks.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Therefore, even new systems usually contain one or more batch applications for updating information at the end of the day, generating reports, printing documents, and other non-interactive tasks that must complete reliably within certain business deadlines.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Some applications are amenable to flow processing, namely those that only need data from a single input at once (not totals, for instance): start the next step for each input as it completes the previous step.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] In this case flow processing lowers latency for individual inputs, allowing them to be completed without waiting for the entire batch to finish.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] However, many applications require data from all records, notably computations such as totals.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] In this case the entire batch must be completed before one has a usable result: partial results are not usable.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Modern batch applications make use of modern batch frameworks such as Jem The Bee, Spring Batch or implementations of JSR 352 written for Java, and other frameworks for other programming languages, to provide the fault tolerance and scalability required for high-volume processing.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] In order to ensure high-speed processing, batch applications are often integrated with grid computing solutions to partition a batch job over a large number of processors, although there are significant programming challenges in doing so.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] High volume batch processing places particularly heavy demands on system and application architectures as well.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Architectures that feature strong input/output performance and vertical scalability, including modern mainframe computers, tend to provide better batch performance than alternatives.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Scripting languages became popular as they evolved along with batch processing.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] A *batch window* is "a period of less-intensive online activity", when the computer system is able to run batch jobs without interference from, or with, interactive online systems.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] A bank's *end-of-day (EOD)* jobs require the concept of *cutover*, where transaction and data are cut off for a particular day's batch activity ("deposits after 3 PM will be processed the next day").
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] As requirements for online systems uptime expanded to support globalization, the Internet, and other business needs, the batch window shrank and increasing emphasis was placed on techniques that would require online data to be available for a maximum amount of time.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] The *batch size* refers to the number of work units to be processed within one batch operation.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] The IBM mainframe z/OS operating system or platform has arguably the most highly refined and evolved set of batch processing facilities owing to its origins, long history, and continuing evolution.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Today such systems commonly support hundreds or even thousands of concurrent online and batch tasks within a single operating system image.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] The Unix programs `cron`, `at`, and `batch` (today `batch` is a variant of `at`) allow for complex scheduling of jobs.
[src:background-jobs/batch-processing] Most high-performance computing clusters use batch processing to maximize cluster usage.
[src:background-jobs/celery-software] The execution units, called *tasks*, are executed concurrently on one or more worker nodes using multiprocessing, eventlet or gevent.
[src:background-jobs/celery-software] Tasks can execute asynchronously (in the background) or synchronously (wait until ready).
[src:background-jobs/celery-software] Celery is used in production systems, for services such as Instagram, to process millions of tasks every day.
[src:background-jobs/celery-software] Celery is written in Python, but the protocol can be implemented in any language.
[src:background-jobs/celery-software] It can also operate with other languages using webhooks.
[src:background-jobs/celery-software] There is also a Ruby-Client called RCelery, a PHP client, a Go client, a Rust client, and a Node.js client.
[src:background-jobs/celery-software] Celery requires a message broker to run.
[src:background-jobs/celery-software] As of October 2024, Redis and RabbitMQ are supported and actively maintained and monitored.
[src:background-jobs/celery-software] Amazon SQS is supported and maintained but does not support worker inspection and management at runtime, while Zookeeper and Kafka are currently in experimental development.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The daemon name originates from Chronos, the Greek word for time.
[src:background-jobs/cron] `cron` is generally available on Unix-like operating systems.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The actions of cron are driven by a *crontab* (cron table) file.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The crontab files are stored where the lists of jobs and other instructions to the cron daemon are kept.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Users can have their own individual crontab files and often there is a system-wide crontab file (usually in `/etc` or a subdirectory of `/etc` e.g.
[src:background-jobs/cron] `/etc/cron.d`) that only system administrators can edit.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The syntax of each line expects a cron expression made of five fields which represent the time to execute the command, followed by a shell command to execute.
[src:background-jobs/cron] While normally the job is executed when the time/date specification fields all match the current time and date, there is one exception: if both "day of month" (field 3) and "day of week" (field 5) are restricted (do not contain "*"), then one or both must match the current day.
[src:background-jobs/cron] This example runs a shell program called export_dump.sh at 23:45 (11:45 PM) every Saturday.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Note: On some systems it is also possible to specify `*/n` to run for every *n*-th interval of time.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Also, specifying multiple specific time intervals can be done with commas (e.g., `1,2,3`).
[src:background-jobs/cron] The line below would output "hello world" to the command line every 5th minute of every first, second and third hour (i.e., 01:00, 01:05, 01:10, up until 03:55).
[src:background-jobs/cron] The configuration file for a user can be edited by calling `crontab -e` regardless of where the actual implementation stores this file.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Some `cron` implementations, such as the popular 4th BSD edition written by Paul Vixie and included in many Linux distributions, add a sixth field: an account username that runs the specified job (subject to user existence and permissions).
[src:background-jobs/cron] This is allowed only in the system crontabs—not in others, which are each assigned to a single user to configure.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The sixth field is alternatively sometimes used for *year* instead of an account username—the nncron daemon for Windows does this.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The Amazon EventBridge implementation of cron does not use 0 based day of week, instead it is 1-7 SUN-SAT (instead of 0-6), as well as supporting additional expression features such as first-weekday and last-day-of-month.
[src:background-jobs/cron] `@reboot` configures a job to run once when the daemon is started.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Since cron is typically never restarted, this typically corresponds to the machine being booted.
[src:background-jobs/cron] This behavior is enforced in some variations of cron, such as that provided in Debian, so that simply restarting the daemon does not re-run `@reboot` jobs.
[src:background-jobs/cron] `@reboot` can be useful if there is a need to start up a server or daemon under a particular user, and the user does not have access to configure init to start the program.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Note that if neither of these files exists then, depending on site-dependent configuration parameters, either only the super user can use cron jobs, or all users can use cron jobs.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Most cron implementations simply interpret crontab entries in the system time zone setting that the cron daemon runs under.
[src:background-jobs/cron] This can be a source of dispute if a large multi-user machine has users in several time zones, especially if the system default time zone includes the potentially confusing DST.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Thus, a cron implementation may as a special case recognize lines of the form "CRON_TZ=<time zone>" in user crontabs, interpreting subsequent crontab entries relative to that time zone.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The cron in Version 7 Unix was a system service (later called a daemon) invoked from `/etc/rc` when the operating system entered multi-user mode.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Determine if any commands must run at the current date and time, and if so, run them as the superuser, root.
[src:background-jobs/cron] This version of cron was basic and robust but it also consumed resources whether it found any work to do or not.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In an experiment at Purdue University in the late 1970s to extend cron's service to all 100 users on a time-shared VAX, it was found to place too much load on the system.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The next version of cron, with the release of Unix System V, was created to extend the capabilities of cron to all users of a Unix system, not just the superuser.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Though this may seem trivial today with most Unix and Unix-like systems having powerful processors and small numbers of users, at the time it required a new approach on a one-MIPS system having roughly 100 user accounts.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In the August, 1977 issue of the *Communications of the ACM*, W.
[src:background-jobs/cron] A Purdue graduate student, Robert Brown, reviewing this article, recognized the parallel between cron and discrete event simulators, and created an implementation of the Franta–Maly event list manager (ELM) for experimentation.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Discrete event simulators run in *virtual time*, peeling events off the event queue as quickly as possible and advancing their notion of "now" to the scheduled time of the next event.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Running the event simulator in "real time" instead of virtual time created a version of cron that spent most of its time sleeping, waiting for the scheduled time to execute the task at the head of the event list.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The following school year brought new students into the graduate program at Purdue, including Keith Williamson, who joined the systems staff in the Computer Science department.
[src:background-jobs/cron] As a "warm up task" Brown asked him to flesh out the prototype cron into a production service, and this multi-user cron went into use at Purdue in late 1979.
[src:background-jobs/cron] This version of cron wholly replaced the `/etc/cron` that was in use on the computer science department's VAX 11/780 running 32/V.
[src:background-jobs/cron] For each crontab file found, determine the next time in the future that each command must run.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Place those commands on the Franta–Maly event list with their corresponding time and their "five field" time specifier.
[src:background-jobs/cron] On awakening and after verifying the correct time, execute the task at the head of the queue (in background) with the privileges of the user who created it.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Determine the next time in the future to run this command and place it back on the event list at that time value.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Additionally, the daemon responds to SIGHUP signals to rescan modified crontab files and schedules special "wake up events" on the hour and half-hour to look for modified crontab files.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Much detail is omitted here concerning the inaccuracies of computer time-of-day tracking, Unix alarm scheduling, explicit time-of-day changes, and process management, all of which account for the majority of the lines of code in this cron.
[src:background-jobs/cron] This cron also captured the output of *stdout* and *stderr* and e-mailed any output to the crontab owner.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The resources consumed by this cron scale only with the amount of work it is given and do not inherently increase over time, with the exception of periodically checking for changes.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Williamson completed his studies and departed the University with a Masters of Science in Computer Science and joined AT&T Bell Labs in Murray Hill, New Jersey, and took this cron with him.
[src:background-jobs/cron] This version of cron later appeared largely unchanged in Unix System V and in BSD and their derivatives, Solaris from Sun Microsystems, IRIX from Silicon Graphics, HP-UX from Hewlett-Packard, and AIX from IBM.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Technically, the original license for these implementations should be with the Purdue Research Foundation who funded the work, but this took place at a time when little concern was given to such matters.
[src:background-jobs/cron] With the advent of the GNU Project and Linux, new crons appeared.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The most prevalent of these is the Vixie cron, originally coded by Paul Vixie in 1987.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Version 3 of **Vixie cron** was released in late 1993.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Version 4.1 was renamed to **ISC Cron** and was released in January 2004.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Version 3, with some minor bugfixes, is used in most distributions of Linux and BSDs.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In 2007, Red Hat forked vixie-cron 4.1 to the cronie project, adding features such as PAM and SELinux support.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In 2009, anacron 2.3 was merged into cronie.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Anacron is not an independent cron program however; another cron job must call it.
[src:background-jobs/cron] DragonFly's dcron was made by its founder Matt Dillon, and its maintainership was taken over by Jim Pryor in 2010.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In 2003, Dale Mellor introduced mcron, a cron variant written in Guile which provides cross-compatibility with Vixie cron while also providing greater flexibility as it allows arbitrary scheme code to be used in scheduling calculations and job definitions.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Since both the mcron daemon and the crontab files are usually written in scheme (though mcron also accepts traditional Vixie crontabs), the cumulative state of a user's job queue is available to their job code, which may be scheduled to run iff the results of other jobs meet certain criteria.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Mcron is deployed by default under the Guix package manager, which includes provisions (services) for the package manager to monadically emit mcron crontabs while both ensuring that packages needed for job execution are installed and that the corresponding crontabs correctly refer to them.
[src:background-jobs/cron] A webcron solution schedules ring tasks to run on a regular basis wherever cron implementations are not available in a web hosting environment.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In 2025, the Open Cron Pattern Specification (OCPS) was published to address fragmentation in cron syntax across different implementations.
[src:background-jobs/cron] OCPS 1.0 provides a formal specification of the Vixie cron dialect, codifying the five-field pattern format with explicit rules for previously ambiguous edge cases.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The specification is designed as a backward-compatible superset, with future versions planned to incrementally add features such as predefined schedules, second-level precision, and advanced calendar modifiers while maintaining compatibility with earlier versions.
[src:background-jobs/cron] A cron expression is a string comprising five, six, or seven fields separated by white space that represents a set of times, normally as a schedule to execute some routine.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Comments begin with a comment mark #, and must be on a line by themselves.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The month and weekday abbreviations are not case-sensitive.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In the particular case of the system crontab file (/etc/crontab), a *user* field inserts itself before the *command*.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Asterisks (also known as wildcard) represents "all".
[src:background-jobs/cron] For example, using "* * * * *" will run every minute.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Using "* * * * 1" will run every minute only on Monday.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Using six asterisks means every second when seconds are supported.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Commas are used to separate items of a list.
[src:background-jobs/cron] For example, using "MON,WED,FRI" in the 5th field (day of week) means Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays.
[src:background-jobs/cron] For example, "2000-2010" indicates every year between 2000 and 2010, inclusive.
[src:background-jobs/cron] % are sent to the command as standard input.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The following are non-standard characters and exist only in some cron implementations, such as the Quartz Java scheduler.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In the day-of-month field, it specifies the last day of the month.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The 'W' character is allowed for the day-of-month field.
[src:background-jobs/cron] This character is used to specify the weekday (Monday-Friday) nearest the given day.
[src:background-jobs/cron] " is specified as the value for the day-of-month field, the meaning is: "the nearest weekday to the 15th of the month." So, if the 15th is a Saturday, the trigger fires on Friday the 14th.
[src:background-jobs/cron] If the 15th is a Sunday, the trigger fires on Monday the 16th.
[src:background-jobs/cron] If the 15th is a Tuesday, then it fires on Tuesday the 15th.
[src:background-jobs/cron] However, if "1W" is specified as the value for day-of-month, and the 1st is a Saturday, the trigger fires on Monday the 3rd, as it does not 'jump' over the boundary of a month's days.
[src:background-jobs/cron] The 'W' character can be specified only when the day-of-month is a single day, not a range or list of days.
[src:background-jobs/cron] '#' is allowed for the day-of-week field, and must be followed by a number between one and five.
[src:background-jobs/cron] It allows specifying constructs such as "the second Friday" of a given month.
[src:background-jobs/cron] For example, entering "5#3" in the day-of-week field corresponds to the third Friday of every month.
[src:background-jobs/cron] ' for leaving either day-of-month or day-of-week blank.
[src:background-jobs/cron] if cron started-up on 8:25am, and would run at this time every day until restarted again.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In vixie-cron, slashes can be combined with ranges to specify step values.
[src:background-jobs/cron] in the minutes field indicates every 5 minutes (see note below about frequencies).
[src:background-jobs/cron] POSIX does not define a use for slashes; its rationale (commenting on a BSD extension) notes that the definition is based on System V format but does not exclude the possibility of extensions.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Some language-specific libraries offering crontab scheduling ability do not require "strict" ranges 15-59/XX to the left of the slash when ranges are used.
[src:background-jobs/cron] In these cases, 15/XX is the same as a vixie-cron schedule of 15-59/10 in the minutes section.
[src:background-jobs/cron] Similarly, one can remove the extra -23 from 0-23/XX, -31 from 1-31/XX, and -12 from 1-12/XX for hours, days, and months; respectively.
[src:background-jobs/cron] continuous integration system to indicate that a "hashed" value is substituted.
[src:background-jobs/cron] ' indicates that the task is performed every hour at an unspecified but invariant time for each task.
[src:background-jobs/cron] This allows spreading out tasks over time, rather than having all of them start at the same time and compete for resources.
[src:background-jobs/job-queue] In system software, a **job queue** (a.k.a.
[src:background-jobs/job-queue] **batch queue**, **input queue**), is a data structure maintained by job scheduler software containing jobs to run.
[src:background-jobs/job-queue] Users submit their programs that they want executed, "jobs", to the queue for batch processing.
[src:background-jobs/job-queue] The scheduler software maintains the queue as the pool of jobs available for it to run.
[src:background-jobs/job-queue] Any process that comes to the CPU should wait in a queue.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:background-jobs/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
